liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: But before I go! My colleague Kirsten Aiken spoke to Lindsay Partridge, Brickworks managing director, a little earlier. If you remember, we mentioned Brickworks in the blog at the start of the day because its share price was taking a beating. At that point its share price had fallen by 10%, but it's finished the day down 6.4%. Mr Patridge knows what's happening in the construction industry (obviously), and he had some really interesting things to say about the Albanese government's push to have 1.2 million new homes built within five years. He says it's going to take 500,000 more tradespeople, new land releases, and fewer taxes. Kirsten's team has put a shorter version of that interview together for the blog right now, with the longer version of the interview to air on The Business tonight at 8.45pm AEST.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Bureau of Statistics has also released the latest job vacancies data. Job vacancies fell by 8.9% (37,900 vacancies) in the three months to August (seasonally adjusted). It was the fifth consecutive quarterly decrease, but the level of job vacancies was still 71.5% higher than in February 2020, prior to the start of the pandemic. The ABS says the ongoing high level of vacancies reflects the continuing labour shortages in many industries. The proportion of businesses reporting at least one vacancy is continuing to decline. It fell to 21.7% in August 2023.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Job vacancies decline again, but still elevated
